% ============================================================
% 5. RESEARCH JOURNEY
% ============================================================
\section{Research Journey: Four Experimental Lineages}

This project did not follow a straight line. Each failed approach taught lessons that directly shaped the next attempt. We document all four tracks because the failures were as informative as the successes.

\subsection{Track 1: Documentation-First (v0x) --- Failed}

The project began with an extensive literature review. A survey of 21 research papers was conducted, and documentation was written before any code: architecture specifications, dataset analyses, training plans~--- all generated with AI assistance (Gemini Deep Research, ChatGPT, Codex). The philosophy was ``get the docs right, then build notebooks from them.''

This approach failed when too many ideas from research papers were added simultaneously, leading to untested complexity. There was little to no executable code until late versions.

\textbf{Lesson:} Documentation without experimentation leads to untested assumptions. Ideas must be validated incrementally.

\subsection{Track 2: Kaggle Notebook Reproduction (vK) --- Failed}

A Kaggle notebook (\texttt{image-detection-with-mask}) was discovered that appeared to solve the assignment task: a dual-head UNet with classification and segmentation outputs, reporting $\sim$89.75\% accuracy and Dice $\sim$0.57 on CASIA.

An audit revealed two fatal problems:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Data leakage:} The test CSV pointed to the validation set. Reported ``test accuracy'' was actually validation accuracy.
    \item \textbf{Segmentation failure:} On a dataset where $\sim$40\% of images are authentic (all-zero masks), a model predicting all-zero masks scores Dice $\sim$0.58. The segmentation head was not learning meaningful features.
\end{enumerate}

After fixing the leakage, training from scratch on $\sim$10K RGB images with 31.6M parameters proved insufficient. Best honest Tampered F1 in this track: 0.4101 (v6.5).

\textbf{Lesson:} Always audit for data leakage. Training from scratch on small datasets with large models is insufficient~--- the model memorizes low-level features instead of learning forensic patterns.

\subsection{Track 3: ETASR Classification (vR) --- Archived}

The project pivoted to reproducing a published research paper~\cite{nagm2024etasr}: ``Enhanced Image Tampering Detection using ELA and a CNN'' which reported 96.21\% accuracy using a custom 2-layer CNN on $128 \times 128$ ELA images.

Seven honest ablation experiments (vR.1.1 through vR.1.7) were conducted:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{ETASR Classification Track Results}
\label{tab:etasr}
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
\begin{tabular}{l l c c c l}
\toprule
\textbf{Ver.} & \textbf{Change} & \textbf{Acc} & \textbf{F1} & \textbf{Params} & \textbf{Verdict} \\
\midrule
vR.1.1 & Honest baseline & 88.38 & .8805 & 29.5M & Baseline \\
vR.1.2 & Data augmentation & 85.53 & .8505 & 29.5M & Rejected \\
vR.1.3 & Class weights & 89.17 & .8889 & 29.5M & Positive \\
vR.1.4 & BatchNorm & 88.75 & .8852 & 29.5M & Neutral \\
vR.1.5 & LR scheduler & 88.96 & .8873 & 29.5M & Neutral \\
\textbf{vR.1.6} & \textbf{Deeper CNN} & \textbf{90.23} & \textbf{.9004} & \textbf{13.8M} & \textbf{Best} \\
vR.1.7 & Global Avg Pool & 89.17 & .8901 & 64K & Neutral \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Key findings from this track:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Paper gap:} 5.98pp below the claimed 96.21\%, never closed (likely due to dataset filtering: the paper used JPEG-only images).
    \item \textbf{The Flatten-Dense bottleneck is toxic:} The Flatten layer connecting the final conv map to Dense(256) created a 29.5M-parameter bottleneck (99\%+ of total parameters). It caused data augmentation failure (vR.1.2) because Flatten memorizes exact pixel positions~--- augmented images activate completely different neurons.
    \item \textbf{Architecture $>$ training tricks:} The deeper CNN (vR.1.6, +1.85pp) outperformed class weights + BatchNorm + LR scheduler combined (+0.58pp).
    \item \textbf{Critical limitation:} Classification-only. No pixel-level localization capability.
\end{itemize}

The track was archived because the assignment requires localization.

\textbf{Lesson:} Verify the base architecture supports all required output tasks before investing in ablation studies.

\subsection{Track 4: Pretrained Ablation Study (vR.P) --- Final}

Armed with lessons from all prior failures, the final lineage used:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Pretrained encoder} (ResNet-34 on ImageNet) to avoid the small-dataset problem.
    \item \textbf{UNet segmentation} for pixel-level localization.
    \item \textbf{ELA preprocessing} (from ETASR track insight) as forensic input.
    \item \textbf{Single-variable ablation:} exactly one change per experiment.
    \item \textbf{Weights \& Biases}~\cite{wandb2020} tracking for all experiments.
    \item \textbf{Reproducibility protocol:} seed 42, identical hardware, two verification runs.
\end{itemize}

