\subsection{Ablation by Category}

\subsubsection{Category 1: Input Representation (Dominant Factor)}

This was the most impactful category across the entire study. Table~\ref{tab:input_ablation} shows the input representation experiments.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Input Representation Ablation}
\label{tab:input_ablation}
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
\begin{tabular}{l c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Input Type} & \textbf{Channels} & \textbf{Px F1} & \textbf{$\Delta$ from P.1} \\
\midrule
RGB (P.1) & 3 & 0.4546 & --- \\
ELA gray $\to$ RGB (P.3) & 3 & 0.6920 & +0.2374 \\
RGB + ELA (P.4) & 4 & 0.7053 & +0.2507 \\
Multi-Q ELA gray (P.15) & 3 & 0.7329 & +0.2783 \\
ELA + DCT (P.17) & 6 & 0.7302 & +0.2756 \\
\textbf{Multi-Q RGB ELA (P.19)} & \textbf{9} & \textbf{0.7965} & \textbf{+0.3419} \\
DCT only (P.16) & 3 & 0.3209 & $-$0.1337 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Key observations:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{RGB $\to$ ELA (P.3):} +23.74pp~--- the single largest improvement. False positive rate dropped from 22.6\% to 2.7\%.
    \item \textbf{Grayscale $\to$ RGB ELA (P.15 vs P.19):} Keeping RGB color information in each ELA map was worth +6.36pp over grayscale. The color channels carry additional forensic information about which color channels were manipulated.
    \item \textbf{DCT-only (P.16):} Catastrophic $-$37.11pp failure. Block-level frequency coefficients without spatial ELA context are insufficient for the ResNet encoder, which expects spatially structured input.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Category 2: Encoder Architecture}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Encoder Architecture Comparison (all on RGB input)}
\label{tab:encoder_ablation}
\begin{tabular}{l c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Encoder} & \textbf{Train. Params} & \textbf{Px F1} & \textbf{$\Delta$ from P.1} \\
\midrule
ResNet-34 (P.1) & 3.17M & 0.4546 & --- \\
ResNet-50 (P.5) & 9.0M & 0.5137 & +0.0591 \\
EfficientNet-B0 (P.6) & 2.24M & 0.5217 & +0.0671 \\
ResNet-34 + ELA (P.3) & 3.17M & \textbf{0.6920} & \textbf{+0.2374} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The hierarchy is stark: \textbf{ELA on ResNet-34} (3.17M params, F1=0.6920) vastly outperforms ResNet-50 (9M params, F1=0.5137) and EfficientNet-B0 (2.24M params, F1=0.5217) on RGB. Input representation matters far more than encoder capacity.

\subsubsection{Category 3: Training Strategies}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Training Strategy Ablation (all from ELA baseline P.3)}
\label{tab:training_ablation}
\begin{tabular}{l c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Strategy} & \textbf{Px F1} & \textbf{$\Delta$ from P.3} \\
\midrule
P.3 Baseline (25 epochs) & 0.6920 & --- \\
P.7 Extended (50 epochs) & 0.7154 & +0.0234 \\
P.8 Progressive unfreeze & 0.6985 & +0.0065 \\
P.12 Data augmentation & 0.6968 & +0.0048 \\
P.1.5 AMP/TF32 & 0.4227 & (neutral) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Extended training (P.7):} P.3's best epoch was 25/25 (the max). With 50-epoch budget, the optimum was found at epoch 36, yielding +2.34pp.
    \item \textbf{Progressive unfreeze (P.8):} Best epoch was in the frozen stage (epoch 23), before any unfreezing. Confirms frozen+BN is the sweet spot.
    \item \textbf{Data augmentation (P.12):} Only +0.48pp pixel F1 but achieved the best image accuracy (88.48\%) and image macro F1 (0.8756). Augmentation helps classification robustness more than pixel-level precision.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Category 4: Loss Function}

Focal+Dice (P.9) was essentially neutral (+0.03pp) versus BCE+Dice. Pixel AUC actually regressed by $-$2.05pp because Focal Loss concentrates predictions near 0/1 extremes ($\gamma=2$ suppresses the gradient for well-classified pixels), destroying probability calibration.

\subsubsection{Category 5: Evaluation Strategy}

Test-time augmentation (P.14b) averaged predictions across 4 views (original, H-flip, V-flip, both flips). This achieved the best Pixel AUC (0.9618) and lowest FP rate (1.2\%) but \textit{destroyed} Pixel F1 ($-$5.32pp). Averaging smooths sharp mask boundaries, hurting localization precision.

\subsection{Impact Hierarchy}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Complete Impact Hierarchy (Delta from ELA baseline P.3)}
\label{tab:impact}
\begin{tabular}{c l l c}
\toprule
\textbf{\#} & \textbf{Category} & \textbf{Change} & \textbf{$\Delta$ F1 (pp)} \\
\midrule
1 & Input & Multi-Q RGB ELA 9ch & +10.45 \\
2 & Input & Multi-Q ELA gray & +4.09 \\
3 & Input & ELA+DCT fusion & +3.82 \\
4 & Architecture & CBAM attention & +3.57 \\
5 & Training & Extended training & +2.34 \\
6 & Input & RGB+ELA fusion & +1.33 \\
7 & Training & Progressive unfreeze & +0.65 \\
8 & Training & Augmentation & +0.48 \\
9 & Loss & Focal+Dice & +0.03 \\
10 & Evaluation & TTA & $-$5.32 \\
11 & Input & DCT-only & $-$37.11 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The hierarchy is clear:
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\text{Input} \gg \text{Attention} > \text{Training} > \text{Loss}}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Parameter Efficiency Analysis}

CBAM provides the highest improvement density of any modification:
\begin{equation}
    \text{Efficiency}_{\text{CBAM}} = \frac{3.57\,\text{pp}}{11{,}402\,\text{params}} = 0.313\,\text{pp per 1K params}
\end{equation}

By contrast:
\begin{equation}
    \text{Efficiency}_{\text{ResNet-50}} = \frac{5.91\,\text{pp}}{5{,}830{,}000\,\text{extra params}} = 0.001\,\text{pp per 1K params}
\end{equation}

CBAM is $\sim$300$\times$ more parameter-efficient than upgrading the encoder.

\subsection{Diminishing Returns}

After Pixel F1 $\sim$0.78, combining improvements shows diminishing returns:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item P.19 alone: F1 = 0.7965
    \item P.30.1 (P.19 + CBAM + 50ep): F1 = 0.7762 ($<$ P.19)
    \item P.30.4 (P.19 + CBAM + aug): F1 = 0.7745 ($<$ P.19)
\end{itemize}

This suggests the model is approaching the ceiling of what the dataset and architecture can support. The 9-channel RGB ELA representation may already capture most of the forensic signal available in CASIA v2.0.

% ============================================================
% 7. ERROR ANALYSIS
% ============================================================
\section{Error Analysis}

\subsection{False Positive and False Negative Rates}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Image-Level Error Rates Across Configurations}
\label{tab:error_rates}
\begin{tabular}{l c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Config} & \textbf{FP Rate} & \textbf{FN Rate} & \textbf{$\Delta$FP} \\
\midrule
RGB baseline (P.1) & 22.6\% & 40.4\% & --- \\
ELA baseline (P.3) & 2.7\% & 28.6\% & $-$19.9pp \\
CBAM (P.10) & 2.0\% & 28.3\% & $-$0.7pp \\
Augmentation (P.12) & 2.6\% & 24.6\% & $-$0.1pp \\
TTA (P.14b) & 1.2\% & 29.3\% & $-$1.5pp \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

ELA reduces the false positive rate by 19.9 percentage points (22.6\% $\to$ 2.7\%). CBAM further drops it to 2.0\%. The remaining errors are primarily false negatives.

\subsection{Failure Modes}

The model struggles with three specific failure modes:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Subtle copy-move forgeries:} When source and target textures are very similar, the ELA residuals are nearly identical, providing no forensic signal.
    \item \textbf{Very small tampered regions} ($<$2\% of image area): The 384$\times$384 resolution and the encoder's downsampling lose fine boundary details for tiny manipulations.
    \item \textbf{Multi-generation JPEG:} Images re-saved multiple times have uniform compression artifacts everywhere, destroying the differential ELA signal between authentic and tampered regions.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Precision-Recall Trade-off}

The best model (P.15 detailed metrics available) achieves:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Complete Metrics for Grayscale-ELA Model (P.15)}
\label{tab:detailed_metrics}
\begin{tabular}{l c l}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Value} & \textbf{Interpretation} \\
\midrule
Pixel F1 & 0.7329 & Primary metric \\
Pixel IoU & 0.5785 & Stricter overlap \\
Pixel AUC & 0.9608 & Discrimination quality \\
Pixel Precision & 0.8409 & Few false alarms \\
Pixel Recall & 0.6496 & Misses some regions \\
Image Accuracy & 87.53\% & Detection accuracy \\
Image Macro F1 & 0.8660 & Balanced class perf \\
Image ROC-AUC & 0.9423 & Ranking quality \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The model is conservative: high precision (0.8409) means it rarely flags authentic regions as tampered, but moderate recall (0.6496) means it misses about 35\% of tampered pixels. This trade-off is acceptable for forensic applications where false accusations are costly.

